Task 1:
CONFIDENTIALITY CLAUSE

1.1 This Confidentiality Clause ("Clause") forms part of the Agreement ("Agreement") between Company A ("Company A") and Company B ("Company B") (collectively, the "Parties").

1.2 For the purposes of this Clause, "Proprietary Information" means any and all confidential, proprietary, and trade secret information, including but not limited to:

(a) trade secrets and confidential business information;
(b) research and development data;
(c) technical information and specifications;
(d) business strategies and plans;
(e) customer and supplier information;
(f) financial information and forecasts;
(g) marketing and sales data; and
(h) any other confidential information of either Party.

1.3 Each Party agrees to keep all Proprietary Information confidential and not to disclose it to any third party without the prior written consent of the disclosing Party.

1.4 The obligations of confidentiality under this Clause shall continue for a period of three (3) years from the date of disclosure of the Proprietary Information.

1.5 Notwithstanding the foregoing, the obligations of confidentiality under this Clause shall not apply to any Proprietary Information that:

(a) is or becomes publicly available through no fault of the receiving Party;
(b) is already in the possession of the receiving Party at the time of disclosure;
(c) is obtained by the receiving Party from a third party who has the right to disclose it;
(d) is required to be disclosed by law or by a court or other governmental authority; or
(e) is disclosed in accordance with the terms of this Agreement.

1.6 Upon request, each Party shall return all Proprietary Information to the disclosing Party, and shall destroy all copies of such information in its possession.

Task 2:
This Confidentiality Clause is a standard provision in contracts between companies to protect sensitive information. In simple terms, it means that both Company A and Company B agree to keep each other's confidential information secret for a period of three years.

The implications of this clause are that both parties must be careful not to disclose any confidential information to third parties, and must return or destroy any confidential information upon request. If either party breaches this clause, the other party may seek damages or other remedies.

An example scenario where this clause might be invoked is if Company A shares its proprietary research and development data with Company B, and Company B then discloses this information to a competitor without permission. In this case, Company A could claim that Company B has breached the confidentiality clause and seek damages for the unauthorized disclosure.

